title: Avoid segmentation fault when creating session with TRT EP or OpenVINO EP using python
body:
When creating ort session with TRT EP or OpenVINO EP in an environment where dependencies are not installed or not in the LD_LIBRARY_PATH, in some cases, it will cause segmentation fault due to not properly handle return value. 
issue is described in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/9747

This PR fixes this issue as well as makes TRT EP follow the same pattern as CUDA EP. 
Which means when user explicitly sets TRT EP but having one of following situation:

> 1. ORT_TENSORRT_UNAVAILABLE is set to 1 by _ld_preload.py (in manylinux only)

> 2. ORT_TENSORRT_UNAVAILABLE/CUDA_PATH not being set and TRT libraries are not installed or not in the LD_LIBRARY_PATH

TRT EP will be skipped and fallback to other EPs.

title: WinML RT API: Add PixelRange Metadata to Bind() call PropertySet
body:
Issue: The WinML RT API supports support setting model metadata to indicate normalization schemes and pixel formats for model inputs. The Bind() call supports setting or overriding input metadata properties like BitmapPixelFormat, and Bounds, but currently does not allow users to override the input normalization mode: LearningModelPixelRange.

The LearningModelPixelRange enum defines the normalization scheme, currently allows for direct image tensorization when the normalization scheme is specified manually on the model using the WinML Dashboard. Models without the metadata specified cannot take advantage of this automatic tensorization feature.

This change enables specifying the PixelRange metadata as a Bind property, so callers can still inform the WinML RT API of their needed normalization mode when models don't have the metadate specified in the onnx model file.

title: Dynamic cost model to mitigate high E2E perf variance
body:
Addressing [issue](https://microsoft-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jianm_microsoft_com/_layouts/15/onedrive.aspx?id=%2Fpersonal%2Fjianm%5Fmicrosoft%5Fcom%2FDocuments%2FMicrosoft%20Teams%20Chat%20Files%2FOnnxRuntimePerfEvaluation%2Ehtml&parent=%2Fpersonal%2Fjianm%5Fmicrosoft%5Fcom%2FDocuments%2FMicrosoft%20Teams%20Chat%20Files)

Research showed that the constant cost model now utilized in thread pool split tasks with big granularity, sometimes this helps to infer the model faster,  while sometimes it is causing high E2E latency since occasionally there is a thread, after acquiring a large shard of task, get preempted from execution.

To battle the problem, we devised an approach to compute the block size on the fly - the block size starts from 
```
total_number_of_iterations /  (num_of_threads * dynamic_block_base)
```
And it will diminish according to the changing residual. This way, when the task is approaching completion, the preempted thread (if there is any) will take a shard that is way smaller, allowing sibling threads to keep contributing for parallelism.
Tests on D32s (with 13 threads) suggest variance reduction as below:

title: Move part of the GatherGrad computation to GatherInternal
body:
Work in this pull request is aimed at mitigating the impact of the memcpys required for performing `GatherGrad` to the performance of the model (latency wise).

In a few examples we have seen, the memcpys of `GatherGrad` were causing significant idleness in the CUDA stream as is seen in this example:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12852605/143149752-f77f560f-cbee-412b-8f1d-1a84a008d72d.png)

It turns out that these memcpys are required for computing information necessary for `GatherGrad`. However, this information depends on information already available to `Gather` and does not need to wait to be computed when `GatherGrad` is invoked. Work in this pull request tries to pre compute this information at the time of forward op execution (execution of the `GatherInternal` node) so that all the data is available for `GatherGrad` to execute without needing to perform these memcpys.

Here is the visual profile of the compute stream when part of the `GatherGrad` computation is moved upstream to `GatherInternal`:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12852605/143150683-8b530697-d95d-40af-b8d5-961997f2fa7b.png)

Performance improvement of around 2.6% was observed with this change on an internal model.

Work in this pull request:
1. Graph transformation to replace every `Gather` node with a `GatherInternal` node for the cuda device. This transformation is triggered before the gradient has been built.
2. Graph transformation to replace every `GatherInternal` node with a `Gather` node when the extra outputs are not needed (in the case where the `GatherInternal` node is not connected to a `GatherGrad` node). This transformation is triggered after the gradient has been built.
3. Pass in the device information from the `GraphExecutionManager` in the frontend to the graph transformer utils in the backend so that the graph transformers can be correctly applied according to the device being used.
3. Moving computation that required memcpy from `GatherGrad` to `GatherInternal`.

title: Fix potential data race with OrtValue usage in Python
body:
**Description**: 

Problem: When a user creates an `OrtValue` using `OrtValue.ortvalue_from_numpy`,  `cudaMemcpy()` is used to copy contents of the numpy array into cuda device memory. The default stream is used to do this (since OrtValue creation is not tied to a particular session). The [CUDA API doc](https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-runtime-api/api-sync-behavior.html#api-sync-behavior__memcpy-sync) states that:

"For transfers from pageable host memory to device memory, a stream sync is performed before the copy is initiated. The function will return once the pageable buffer has been copied to the staging memory for DMA transfer to device memory, but the DMA to final destination may not have completed."

This means that without an explicit sync, the copy between pageable host memory and device memory is not guaranteed to have completed when the `OrtValue` is constructed and ready for use. In our sessions, we use non-blocking compute streams (streams that do not implicitly sync with the default stream) and hence if a user were to send in a CUDA based OrtValue immediately after construction from a numpy array, there could be a data race leading to bad results.

Fix: Sync after the `cudaMemcpy()` used in OrtValue creation.  

**Motivation and Context**
Resolve https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/9799

title: Use QuantizeLinear rather than dynamic quantization in quantize_qat() when weight is transposed before MatMul
body:
**Description**
1. Add transpose output to quantization_params if it follows fake quantization
2. Handle fake quantization starting with DequantizeLinear due to QuantizeLinear propagating backwards during opt.

**Motivation and Context**
Running quantize_qat() on fine tuned i8 BERT models with fake quantization nodes in [MLPerf](https://github.com/mlcommons/inference/tree/master/language/bert) results in dynamic quantization ops being added on the weights of MatMuls with constant value.
This is because MatMul is from torch.nn.Linear, which adds transpose on the weight resulting in the ONNX model having `weight -> QDQ -> transpose->MatMul`.
By adding transpose's output to quantization_params using QDQ's scale and zero_point value, QuantizeLinear will be used instead.
Furthermore, in the same model, QuantizeLinear is actually constant propagated backwards on the weight initializer during model optimization, leaving only DequantizeLinear behind. Handle this case when removing fake quantization nodes.

title: Cancel transpose optimizer for resize
body:
Fix #9857.
Crash occurs [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/a3ebc5e08290b4000e8509d21819d7f486e23a14/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/upsample.cc#L566).
The model referred in the issue has:
```
[NHWC]->transpose->resize[NCHW]->transpose->[NHWC]
```
By this [PR](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/9607), it optimizes to:
```
[NHWC]->resize[NHWC]->[NHWC]
```
Logically, the optimization is impeccable. 
However, upsample op called from within resize op has been hard-coded to only support NCHW [...](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/1e9e57df3efddc2fc41540e79149e670ac5304c6/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/upsample.cc#L1130)

```
      const int64_t batch_size = is_2D ? 1 : dims[0];
      const int64_t num_channels = is_2D ? 1 : dims[1];
      const int64_t input_height = is_2D ? dims[0] : dims[2];
      const int64_t input_width = is_2D ? dims[1] : dims[3];
      const int64_t output_height = is_2D ? output_dims[0] : output_dims[2];
      const int64_t output_width = is_2D ? output_dims[1] : output_dims[3];
```
When fed with NHWC, the op will mistake H as C, W as H and C as W, which finally traps ort with invalid memory access.

title: add s8s8 support for quantized conv and gemm
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
Add support of S8S8 quantization format, with which both activation and weight are quantized in int8 format. This PR adds s8s8 implementation on ARM devices for operators: QLinearConv, QLinearMatMul.

QGEMM is the most complex part in the change. Here are the dispatchers for quantized gemm:
|      | ARM64 with dot product           | ARM64                            | ARM32                                    |
|------|----------------------------------|----------------------------------|------------------------------------------|

title: Improve reduced ops and types build
body:
**Description**: Improve reduced ops and types build

**Motivation and Context**
- The current reduced build will modify the kernel registration and type controls directly, this has 2 problems,
1. May cause accidental commit of the modified kernel registration and type specification
2. If user modifies the required types and ops after initial build, the modified kernel registration and type specification must be reverted, which is not obvious to users and often ignored and causing missing kernel in execution
- Modify the reduced build to modify the kernel registration and type specification in copied files instead of the original files, and use compile definition to control which file to use, to prevent the issues listed above
- Fixed small test issue in Reduced CI
